{
  "pattern": {
    "name": "unsigned-add-overflow-compare-equivalence",
    "summary": "For an integer sum S = add X, Y, the unsigned comparisons of S against either addend are equivalent overflow predicates: (S <u X) == (S <u Y). Dually, the no-overflow predicates are equivalent: (S >=u X) == (S >=u Y). The same equivalence holds under operand/predicate commutation: (X >u S) == (Y >u S) and (X <=u S) == (Y <=u S). Therefore, when two icmps are formed from the same add result and the two add operands, InstCombine can treat them as implied-equal conditions and fold boolean combinations such as `or`/`and` with duplicate-equivalent predicates to a single compare.",
    "match_conditions": [
      "There exists an integer add `%s = add Ty %x, %y`.",
      "Two unsigned icmps compare `%s` with `%x` and `%y` respectively, possibly with operands swapped.",
      "Predicates must normalize to the same unsigned relation class:",
      "overflow class: `icmp ult %s, %x`, `icmp ult %s, %y`, `icmp ugt %x, %s`, `icmp ugt %y, %s`",
      "no-overflow class: `icmp uge %s, %x`, `icmp uge %s, %y`, `icmp ule %x, %s`, `icmp ule %y, %s`",
      "Add operand order is irrelevant: `%s = add %x, %y` or `%s = add %y, %x`.",
      "The compares may use either add operand on either side, as long as they refer to the two addends of the same add."
    ],
    "canonical_fold": [
      "Replace `or` of two overflow-class compares with either one compare.",
      "Replace `and` of two no-overflow-class compares with either one compare.",
      "More generally in implied-condition reasoning, one normalized compare implies the other exactly when both refer to the same add result and normalized predicates match (`ULT` with `ULT`, `UGE` with `UGE`)."
    ],
    "notes": [
      "This is the unsigned-add overflow identity: for modular addition S=X+Y, carry-out occurs iff S <u X iff S <u Y.",
      "The no-overflow form is its negation: no carry-out iff S >=u X iff S >=u Y.",
      "Only positive cases are included below."
    ]
  },
